   <abstract displayLabel="Description">Scipio and the Bear, a short account of the manners of black bears and an episode of bear hunting, is from Audubon's "Ornithological Biography, or An Account of the Habits of the Birds of the United States of America" (Philadelphia: Judah Dobson, 1831), 1:479-82.  This manuscript originally was entitled "Bear killing."</abstract>
   <note type="content">Manuscript written on Whatman paper, watermarked 1830.</note>
   <note type="biographical/historical" displayLabel="Biographical Note">John James Audubon was an American ornithologist, naturalist, hunter, and painter.  He painted, cataloged, and described the majority of the birds of North America in a monumental work consisting of 435 hand-colored, life-size prints of 497 bird species, made from engraved copper plates measuring around 39 by 26 inches.  "The Birds of America" was first published as a series of sections between 1827 and 1838.</note>
